{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508464"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:05:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:05:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2757"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2757"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.42,0.27,0.09,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2757"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103190"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2757"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2757"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85627"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1186"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"3000"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6087"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3626"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5802"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6132"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11253"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11490"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36160"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103190"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old woman presents with paresthesia and burning pain in the left upper posteromedial arm, shoulder and axilla region. These altered sensations have been present since she had a left mastectomy and left axillary lymph node clearance for breast cancer three months previously.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely to have been involved in this injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Radial nerve","Axillary nerve","Intercostobrachial nerve","Lateral cutaneous nerve of the arm","Medial cutaneous nerve of the arm"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntercostobrachial nerve is correct.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe intercostobrachial nerve originates from spinal nerve T2. It is the lateral cutaneous branch of the second intercostal nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no motor innervation; it is pure sensory nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensory innervation is to skin of upper posteromedial arm and axilla.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDamage to the intercostobrachial nerve is typically associated with axillary clearance in patients with breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe radial nerve originates from spinal nerves C5-T1. It is a branch of posterior cord of brachial plexus.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMotor innervation is to the posterior compartments of arm and forearm.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensory innervation is to the skin of lower posterior arm, posterior forearm, dorsolateral hand.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThus, injury to this nerve is not consistent with the presentation.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAxillary nerve \u003C/strong\u003Eis incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe axillary nerve originates from spinal nerves C5-C6. It is a branch of posterior cord of brachial plexus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMotor innervation is to deltoid and teres minor.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensory innervation is to skin of upper lateral arm.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe axillary nerve innervates the deltoid, which is responsible for abduction (past initial 15\u00b0 by supraspinatus) of the arm, and sensation over the upper lateral aspect of the arm. Thus, injury to this nerve is not consistent with the presentation.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral cutaneous nerve of the forearm \u003C/strong\u003Eis incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lateral cutaneous nerve of forearm originates from spinal nerves C5-C7. It is the termination of musculocutaneous nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no motor innervation; it is pure sensory nerve.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensory innervation is to skin of lower anterolateral arm.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThus, injury to this nerve is not consistent with the presentation.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedial cutaneous nerve of the forearm \u003C/strong\u003Eis incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe medial cutaneous nerve of forearm originates from spinal nerves C8-T1. It is a branch of medial cord of brachial plexus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no motor innervation; it is pure sensory nerve.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensory innervation is to skin of medial arm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThus, injury to this nerve is not consistent with the presentation.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Damage to the intercostobrachial nerve can occur following axillary clearance, and presents with sensory symptoms such as paresthesia and pain in the upper posteromedial arm, shoulder and axillary region."],"references":["Drake R, Vogl AW, Mitchell AW. Gray\u0027s Anatomy for Students. 3rd edition. Elsevier Health Sciences; April 2014.","Moore KL, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 9th edition. Wolters Kluwer; March 2022","Kim JS, Spiess AM. Surgical Treatment of Intercostal Brachial Nerve Pain after Mastectomy and Axillary Dissection. Plast Reconstr Surg Glob Open. 2021;9(11):e3935. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8594654/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85627"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2757"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85627"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-20T14:44:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-20T14:44:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2757"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103190"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T